		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Tue, Apr 12th 3:41 AM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/db/classes.html?class=14&mid=1090907068526424732&num=21&page=0&post=1&replyto=1113291708405782698"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1113291708405782698></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=290089"><span id=>jquick</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br />23 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=jquick&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I second the beastlord suggestion for a few reasons (a bit long winded I admit):<br><br>1. Any class with a pet can produce more melee DPS in my opinion, at least at lower levels, than most melee types alone. Again just my opinion. This is exaggerated when you get mage summoned pet weapons that can proc at any level(Fist of Xiblat, Muzzle of Mardu, and the haste belt). With a few sets of these and temperance, you could probably be 30 by the end of a good grind. Pet classes are Druid, Shaman, Mage, Necro, Shadow Knight, and Enchanter (have pets, and can charm pets, but not ALWAYS dependable ones).<br><br>2. I feel that the sooner a class gets a pet, the faster they can get to the good levels. If I am not mistaken Druids and Shaman have to wait until mid levels to get pets, thus eliminating them in my eyes. All the other classes get pets within first 10 levels, most at level 1.<br><br>3. Of the pet classes, it would be nice to have a class that can hold agro when necessary and not die immediately in the process. IMO this narrows the field further to Shadow Knights and Beastlords.<br><br>4. Now lets weigh the pros and cons.<br><u>Shadow Knight</u><br>PROS: <br>a. More HP&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>b. Double attack is nice with 2h slash  <br>c. FD is handy  <br>d. Can be a dark elf that can hide  <br>e. self healing lifetaps  <br>f. the potent harm touch  <br>g. back up snare  <br>h. backup fear<br>CONS: <br>a. The SK pet is not necessarily a strong pet until AA's kick in<br>b. No slow  <br>c. No haste  <br>d. In the long run, the epic is more difficult to achieve IMO  <br>e. Not as many buffs<br><u>Beastlord </u><br>PROS: <br>a. Have SoW  <br>b. Have slows  <br>c. Have some powerful pet heals  <br>d. With the right buffs, pets can double as a 3rd group member <br>e. Very good pet hastes  <br>f. bring regen(hp/mana) and later another HP regen  <br>g. Dex buffs to accentuate summoned weapons  <br>h. Epic is easy, just takes patience<br>CONS: <br>a. bruise easier than a knight  <br>b. can't snare  <br>c. can't fear, only blind  <br>d. haste comes late in the levels<br><br>-These are just a few, but I have played both to level 51+ and personally feel that the beastlord wins out over a shadow knight-<br><br>On a side note, if you choose a buffing class, set up the spell list for your friend and save it. Then make a hotbutton or 2 that covers the buffs in the press of a button. <br>example: /cast 1<br>         /pause 40*just a number, may need to be higher or lower*<br>         /cast 5<br>         /pause 40<br>         /cast 2<br>Your friend will love you for this, and the hotbutton can even be used for combat sells if desired.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
